WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.120
Hello everyone, my name is Mike Smith, I'm from Pfizer in the UK, and today I'd like

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:18.840
to talk to you a little bit about becoming an RStudio certified trainer.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:22.600
This isn't advancing for some reason, there you go.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:26.280
So what does RStudio certification training mean?

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:32.200
Well it means that you can understand and also demonstrate that you can apply modern

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:36.439
teaching methods and that you're a subject matter expert for the topic that you're becoming

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:37.439
certified in.

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:43.639
Now in the rest of this talk I'd like to draw an analogy between learning R and teaching

00:00:43.639 --> 00:00:47.840
R and training for and running a marathon.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:54.639
So the first hundred yards is awesome, you're full of energy, you've got a goal in mind,

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:57.360
you know you're going to achieve it and it's fantastic.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:01.959
The last hundred yards is also amazing because you're near the finish line, you know you're

00:01:01.959 --> 00:01:04.000
going to get a medal, right?

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.519
It's the 16 weeks and 26 miles in the middle that's the hard bit.

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:13.559
Now I have completed four marathons, okay?

00:01:13.559 --> 00:01:18.940
I wouldn't recommend that anyone in this room come and ask me how they complete a marathon

00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:20.279
in a specific time.

00:01:20.279 --> 00:01:26.360
I am not a coach for running, but I am a coach for Tidyverse.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:29.099
So if you want to learn about Tidyverse, come and see me.

00:01:29.099 --> 00:01:34.900
But I believe that a lot of time when we look to find people who can do training for us,

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:37.559
we go to people who've used R a lot.

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:41.400
You know we'll ask them, but I would think that there's actually a lot more to teaching

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:48.199
people R than simply getting someone who knows how to do it to tell you how they do it, okay?

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:53.879
So I would say certification training has changed how I approach training quite a lot.

00:01:53.879 --> 00:01:56.639
And I want to give you some examples.

00:01:56.639 --> 00:02:01.519
When you're running, when you go out the door, you better have a plan and a route in mind,

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:02.519
right?

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:06.559
You need to know how far you're going, roughly how long it should take, what your route is

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:11.080
so that your three-mile run doesn't suddenly turn into a six-mile run because you took

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:12.320
a wrong turning.

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:15.399
There is an analogy there perfectly for training.

00:02:15.399 --> 00:02:17.259
This is a concept map.

00:02:17.259 --> 00:02:21.820
As a learner, you want to see what are the concepts in this lesson?

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:23.460
How are they related?

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:27.380
As a trainer, you want to know same stuff.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:29.380
What am I training on in this session?

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:30.580
How are things related?

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:32.460
Do I have a through map?

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:39.059
And also, is there too many things here that I'm trying to train in this one session?

00:02:39.059 --> 00:02:45.059
In a marathon training program, you're going to build up incrementally, bit by bit, little

00:02:45.059 --> 00:02:46.059
bit by little bit.

00:02:46.059 --> 00:02:48.860
You don't go from a one-mile run to a 12-mile run.

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:52.580
Why would you do the same in training and teaching people are?

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:54.179
Build it up incrementally.

00:02:54.179 --> 00:03:00.660
Also, it's really important to leave gaps so that your learners can assimilate what

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:08.020
you're teaching, take it on board, figure out how it works for them, and get ready for

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.979
the next block of training.

00:03:10.979 --> 00:03:15.800
And also, it's really important to have little check-ins, have this kind of assessment that

00:03:16.539 --> 00:03:17.600
says, do you know what?

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:19.279
Let's just stop.

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:24.440
Let's check that I understand what you've done so far, and then kind of check out what

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:29.440
bits I understand, what bits I don't understand.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:37.119
Everybody that comes to your training comes with who they are, what they know already,

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:41.300
what they want to get from the training, what they think you're going to train them on,

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:44.199
and what, eventually, they want to get from it.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:49.960
Now, on the RStudio Education GitHub, you'll see some exemplars of these learner personas.

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:51.800
I encourage you to go and have a look.

00:03:51.800 --> 00:03:54.080
These are three of the ones that are there.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:57.880
And the ideas that they show you give examples of the kinds of people that might come to

00:03:57.880 --> 00:03:59.800
your training.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.360
I encourage everyone, if you're trying to set up training, think of the people who are

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:09.039
coming, what their goals are, and then try to address their goals.

00:04:09.039 --> 00:04:13.740
Now, the first time you run a mile, it's a big deal.

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:17.940
You may have started on the couch, and the first time you can run that mile without stopping,

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:21.100
it's a big deal, and it should be celebrated.

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:25.859
I would guess that everyone in this room has completely forgotten what it's like to turn

00:04:25.859 --> 00:04:29.540
an hour on for the first time.

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:30.980
Help these folks out.

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:36.299
By the time you can run six miles, a three-mile session is easy.

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:41.220
So things that we might feel are just a given.

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:42.220
It's trivial.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:43.220
It's easy.

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:50.779
But for long-term R users, it might be indistinguishable from magic for your average beginner.

00:04:50.779 --> 00:04:55.540
So the ideal in this journey is that you get your learners from that first hundred yards

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:59.380
where they're feeling, hey, I'm going to learn something new, this is going to be awesome,

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:03.100
to the end where they're crossing the finish line and getting their medal, and help them

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:07.779
do that and achieve their goals, not what you want them to learn, and to do that as

00:05:07.779 --> 00:05:09.779
quickly as possible.

00:05:09.779 --> 00:05:10.779
Thanks very much.

